d variant of   McCann   or of <b>McCanny</b>, which is an Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Annaidh</b> ‘son of <i>Annadh</i>’ (a personal name of uncertain meaning). In their Anglicized forms the two surnames were confused.","Irish: from <b>Ó Caithniadh</b> ‘son of <i>Caithnia</i>’, a personal name meaning ‘battle champion’, Anglicized as <i>Caheny</i> or <i>Canny</i>."],"variants":[{"name":"McCann","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Brendan, Malachy, Donovan, Liam, Aidan, Aileen, Brigid, Colum, Conan, Donal, Kiernan, Ronan.","Irish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Cana</b> ‘son of <i>Cana</i>’, a personal name based on <i>cana</i> ‘wolf cub’."]},{"name":"Canney","meanings":["Irish (Donegal): variant of   Canny  ."]}]},{"name":"Aubert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Old French name of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>hug</i> ‘heart, mind, spirit’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’. It was popular among the Normans, who introduced it to Britain, where it was later reinforced by settlers from the Low Countries. An 8th-century  St Hubert  succeeded  St Lambert  as bishop of Maastricht and is regarded as the patron of hunters, since, like  St Eustace , he is supposed to have seen a vision of Christ crucified between the antlers of a stag."],"variants":[{"name":"Hupprecht","meanings":["Old French name of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>hug</i> ‘heart, mind, spirit’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’. It was popular among the Normans, who introduced it to Britain, where it was later reinforced by settlers from the Low Countries. An 8th-century  St Hubert  succeeded  St Lambert  as bishop of Maastricht and is regarded as the patron of hunters, since, like  St Eustace , he is supposed to have seen a vision of Christ crucified between the antlers of a stag."]},{"name":"Huppert","meanings":["Old French name of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>hug</i> ‘heart, mind, spirit’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’. It was popular among the Normans, who introduced it to Britain, where it was later reinforced by settlers from the Low Countries. An 8th-century  St Hubert  succeeded  St Lambert  as bishop of Maastricht and is regarded as the patron of hunters, since, like  St Eustace , he is supposed to have seen a vision of Christ crucified between the antlers of a stag."]},{"name":"Hugbert","meanings":["Old French name of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>hug</i> ‘heart, mind, spirit’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’. It was popular among the Normans, who introduced it to Britain, where it was later reinforced by settlers from the Low Countries. An 8th-century  St Hubert  succeeded  St Lambert  as bishop of Maastricht and is regarded as the patron of hunters, since, like  St Eustace , he is supposed to have seen a vision of Christ crucified between the antlers of a stag."]}]},{"name":"de","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["‘Bright’."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Aubert de Canny was born about 1360, in Picardie, Aisne, Picardie, France, his father, Raoul de Flamenc, was 31 and his mother, Marie de Clermont-Nesle, was 17. He married Yolande dite Mariette d'ENGHEIM in 1389. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter."},"et":{"Abt 1360–":"umbes 1360–Surnud","1360–Male":"1360–Surnud","–1408":"–1408","1400–1460":"1400–1460","1330–Male":"1330–Surnud","1344–Female":"1344–Surnud","Abt 1360":"umbes 1360","1389":"1389","1400":"1400","1344":"1344","1330":"1330"," 1400":"1400","1460":"1460","1360":"1360","1408":"1408","Picardie, Aisne, Picardie, France":"Picardie, Aisne, Picardie, Prantsusmaa","France":"Prantsusmaa"},"fi":{"Abt 1360–":"noin 1360–Kuollut","1360–Male":"1360–Kuollut","–1408":"–1408","1400–1460":"1400–1460","1330–Male":"1330–Kuollut","1344–Female":"1344–Kuollut","Abt 1360":"noin 1360","1389":"1389","1400":"1400"